6\. Classification Principle

A coherent boundary separates what the framework addresses from what it
does not. The framework resolves *structural* questions: why this
signature, this dimensionality, this arrow of time, this information
scaling, this mass distinction, this locality. It is silent on
*parametric* questions: why these coupling constants, these masses, this
cosmological constant, this generation count. This boundary is itself a
prediction: the structural features are forced by topology and
combinatorics; the parametric features require additional input that the
five axioms do not provide.

7\. What Remains

One computation. The spin-3 anomalous dimension γ₃ at the K₄ quantum
critical point with V₄-invariant interactions. This is a well-defined
determinantal quantum Monte Carlo problem. It requires GPU-scale
computation and expertise in lattice fermion simulations. The companion
document (computation_requirements.docx) specifies the model, method,
observables, parameters, and interpretation guide. If γ₃ \> 2, the
five-axiom framework derives 3+1 Einstein gravity from informational
principles. If not, it derives a more exotic higher-spin theory. Either
outcome is a definitive result.

*The next computation is the last one the framework requires.*
